ðŸ“˜ Day 22 â€“ Git Tags (Repo Summary)

Today I learned about Git Tags, which are used to mark important points in a repositoryâ€™s history such as releases, versions, and milestones. Tags make it easy to identify, revisit, and manage specific versions of a project.

ðŸ”¹ What are Git Tags?

Tags act like labels on commits.

Commonly used for release management (e.g., v1.0, v2.1.3).

Help teams quickly check out or reference stable versions.

ðŸ”¹ Types of Git Tags

Lightweight Tags
Simple pointers to a commit, quick to create, no metadata.

git tag v1.0-lw

Annotated Tags
Full Git objects with message, author, and date. Recommended for releases.

git tag -a v1.0 -m "Release version 1.0"

ðŸ”¹ Viewing & Using Tags

List all tags:

git tag

git tag -l

Search tags by pattern:

git tag -l "v1*"

View tag details:

git show v1.0

Checkout a tagged version (detached HEAD):

git checkout v1.0

ðŸ”¹ Managing Tags

Delete local tag:

git tag -d v1.0

Delete remote tag:

git push origin --delete v1.0

Move a tag to another commit:

Delete â†’ recreate â†’ push again

Force update a tag:

git tag -f v1.0

git push origin -f v1.0

ðŸ”¹ Best Practices

Use semantic versioning: vMAJOR.MINOR.PATCH

Prefer annotated tags for releases

Avoid force-updating tags unless necessary

Communicate tag changes in team environments

ðŸ“Œ Key Takeaway:
Git tags provide a clean and reliable way to manage releases and milestones, making version control more structured and production-read